==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|lof}}. ''Collins English Dictionary'' states that this word is ultimately derived from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{m|dum|loef}}.<ref>{{R:Dictionary.com}}</ref> Ellert Ekwall's ''Shakspere's Vocabulary: its etymological elements'' (1903) related this verb and {{m|en|loof}} instead to the East Frisian<!--caution: has no code! frs is ambiguous, see BP discussion--> verb ''lofen'', ''lufen'', which would make it cognate to the French term {{m|fr|lover}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/lʌf/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʌf|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|nautical}} The [[vertical]] [[edge]] of a [[sail]] that is closest to the direction of the [[wind]].
#: {{ux|en|By easing the halyard, the '''luff''' of the sail was made to sag to leeward.}}
# {{lb|en|nautical}} The act of sailing a ship close to the wind.
# {{lb|en|nautical}} The roundest part of a ship's [[bow]].
# {{lb|en|nautical}} The [[forward]] or [[weather]] [[leech]] of a sail, especially of the [[jib]], [[spanker]], and other [[fore-and-aft]] sails.

